Valve shape lanceolate to elliptical-lanceolate with rounded ends (
Figs 2–20
). Valve length 2.1–3.1 µm, width 2.3–5.5 µm, and length-width ratio 2.1–3.1 (n=20). Raphe filiform and straight in a raised slightly asymmetric non-perforated sternum (
Figs 16–22
). Axial area narrowing near the valve apices, forming two longitudinal depressions, enlarged in the middle and creating an almost lanceolate central area (
Figs 15–17, 20
). Shape and size of the central area varies. External proximal raphe endings slightly expanded and teardrop-shaped (
Figs 15–17, 20–21
). Distal raphe endings curved in the same direction and extending up to the valve margin (
Figs 15–17, 20
, 
22
). Small elongated helictoglossae present on the distal raphe endings (
Fig. 23
). Raphe sternum well developed but without a conopeum (
Fig. 21
). Striae uniseriate (
20–24 in
10 μm), radiate, becoming strongly radiate towards the apices (
Figs 2–20
). Large specimens exhibit low density or lack of striae in the central part of the valve (
Fig. 19
). Areolae almost square (
Figs 15–20
). Individual areolae not visible in LM. In internal view, the areolae are covered by hymen (
Fig. 23
). Few areolae (2–4) present close to the valve apices on the valve mantle (
Figs 16
, 
22, 24
).
